    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nSetting `vim.g.myvar` to `nil` removes the variable, as per vimscript `:unlet`.\r\nSetting `myvar` to `nil` using `nvim_set_var()` sets it to `nil` (lua) and `v:null` (vimscript).\r\n\r\nThe same is true of `vim.b.myvar` and `nvim_buf_set_var()`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n:lua vim.g.TEST = \"test\"\r\n:echo exists(\"TEST\")\r\n\" 1\r\n:lua vim.g.TEST = nil\r\n:echo exists(\"TEST\")\r\n\" 0\r\n:lua vim.g.TEST = \"test\"\r\n:echo exists(\"TEST\")\r\n\" 1\r\n:lua vim.api.nvim_set_var(\"TEST\", nil)\r\n:echo exists(\"TEST\")\r\n\" 1\r\n: echo TEST\r\n\" v:null\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nHaving used vim.g and vim.b for some time I was used to \"unletting\" variables by setting them to `nil`. I expected, perhaps naively, that `nvim_set_var()` would behave the same. I suspect there are good technical reasons for why they do not, in which case it would help inexperienced users if the help documentation for these features explained how they differ.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.9.5\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\ncannot test lua commands in vim\n\n### Operating system/version\n\ndebian linux 6.5.13-1 (2023-11-29)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.12.2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nscreen-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nappimage",
